    "v n ∈ L 1 such that (i) ∥v n ∥ L 1 ≥ 1, (ii) sup ω∈B P d |⟨Em(ω), v n ⟩| ≤ 1 n. Using the second item, we have sup    Q u n f det DπdL d: ∥f ∥ L n j=1 Lip(π j) ≤ 1    ≤ sup Q u n i f i det Dπ i dL d: s( i (f i, π i)) ≤ 1 = sup ω∈B P d |⟨Em(ω), v n ⟩| ≤ 1 n,and so the sequence v n satisfies the required properties from Definition 1.3.In light of Corollary 4.6 and Theorem 3.18, our next goal will be to assert that Em is strongly non-surjective.",
    "Strong Lipschitz non-regularity of the prescribed Jacobian equationIn this section, we show that if d ≥ 2, then Em is strongly non-surjective and that therefore the prescribed Jacobian equation has strong Lipschitz non-regularity.",
    "We recall the convention that the differential dL d is usually omitted from integration notation and so we write for exampleQ f det Dπ = Q f det DπdL d.Throughout this section, the letter Q will generally be used to denote a generic cube in R d and not refer to the unit cube [0, 1] d. Average determinantsGiven a set E and a map f: E → R, we use the notation∥f ∥ ℓ ∞ (E) = sup x∈E |f (x)|.We shall also use σ to denote the surface measure of the boundary of the unit cube [0, 1] d. Lemma 5.1.",
    "For every d ∈ N, d ≥ 2, there exists a constant c d ∈ (0, ∞) such that the following holds.",
    "For every cube Q ⊂ R d of side length r > 0, and every pair of Lipschitz maps π, κ:Q → R d, it holds that | Q det Dπ - Q det Dκ| ≤ c d L d-1 r d-1 ∥π -κ∥ ℓ ∞ (∂Q), (5.1)where L is the maximum of the Lipschitz constants of the functions π 1,..., π d, κ 1,..., κ d. The constant c d may be taken as the product of the number d and the number of faces a d dimensional cube has.Proof."
